<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900604-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>900604-0054.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>06/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   DONALD TRUMP is in intense talks with bank creditors thatcould force him to give up big chunks of his empire. Thebankers, concerned about the developer's critical cashshortage, are likely to seek asset sales, new management anda much more conservative operating style.   ---</LP><TEXT>   The Dow Jones industrials closed above 2900 for the firsttime Friday as stocks and bonds surged in anticipation offalling interest rates. The stock average rose 24.31 to2900.97. Last week's record-setting equity prices alsoreflect rising expectations for 1990 and 1991 corporateearnings.   ---   Private-sector payrolls barely grew in May after shrinkingin April, the government said. But temporary census hiringlowered the civilian unemployment rate to 5.3% from 5.4%.Meanwhile, the purchasing managers' index of manufacturinghealth rose to its highest level since April 1989.                                                                                                          The soft jobs picture is leading economists to pruneforecasts of second-quarter gross national product.   ---   The Soviet Union is depositing large amounts of gold withWestern banks as collateral for loans. Trade creditors owedhundreds of millions of dollars have been hounding thecashpoor Soviets for overdue payments.   ---   Chevron and the Soviets agreed to study the feasibility ofjointly developing the huge Tengiz oil field. It could be thebiggest U.S.-Soviet venture yet.   ---   Steel prices are rising, leading some firms to restartblast furnaces and to recall workers laid off last fall. Therebound reflects brisk demand -- especially auto-related --higher raw-material costs, and falling imports.   ---   Hitachi will unveil a mainframe computer this week farmore powerful than those on the market, boosting the Japanesecompany's bid to become a major player in the U.S.   ---   Manville Corp. was ordered back to bankruptcy court by twojudges who urged changes in the funding and operation of atrust that the company formed to pay asbestos claims.   ---   L.A. Gear disclosed it will post its first quarterly dropin profit in three years. The news sent the sneaker maker'sstock plunging 22% to $30.75.   ---   Japan's current-account and overall trade surplusesnarrowed sharply in April. Tokyo is considering altering itspolicy of reducing the surpluses.   ---   The failure of Western Sandamp;L will add $1.7 billion to thethrift-bailout cost, more than any other single rescue.BankAmerica bought the Phoenix thrift's deposits, branchesand certain other assets for $81 million.   ---   Esprit's married founders settled their feud as DougTompkins agreed to quit as image director and sell his 50%stake in the apparel firm's U.S. operations to SusieTompkins.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 187,860,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2900.97, up 24.31; transportation 1189.42, up 17.89;utilities 211.71, up 0.32.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3417.62, up43.59.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.87, off 0.22;spot index 133.34, off 0.46.   Dollar: 151.85 yen, off 0.25; 1.6980 marks, up 0.0015.</TEXT></DOC>